# Collections: List Interface

Lists store multiple elements dynamically (unlike arrays).

## ArrayList

Based on arrays, fast random access.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;

ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
numbers.add(10);    // Add
numbers.add(20);
numbers.add(30);

System.out.println(numbers.get(0));  // Access: 10
numbers.remove(1);  // Remove
System.out.println(numbers.size());  // Size: 2
```

## LinkedList

Based on linked nodes, faster insertion/deletion.

```java
import java.util.LinkedList;

LinkedList<String> names = new LinkedList<>();
names.add("Alice");
names.add("Bob");
names.addFirst("Zoe");  // Add at beginning
names.addLast("Charlie"); // Add at end
```

## Iterating Lists

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(1);
list.add(2);
list.add(3);

// for loop
for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
    System.out.println(list.get(i));
}

// for-each
for (int num : list) {
    System.out.println(num);
}
```

